The paper presents a new sorting algorithm that is cache-efficient, parallel, and in-place. This suggests that it belongs to the categories of data structures (cs.DS) and parallel computing (cs.DC). The algorithm is based on distribution-based algorithms, which are commonly used in sorting, and the paper introduces new ways to make them in-place. This suggests that the paper may also belong to the categories of probability and statistics (cs.PF) and programming languages (cs.PL), as these fields often deal with algorithmic design and analysis. Finally, the paper discusses the scalability of the algorithm on multi-core machines, which suggests that it may also belong to the category of distributed computing (cs.Distributed Computing).
